{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d61b84e9-7df5-4b74-8d52-a2afe8e282d5","content":"This is a **TUnit** project, which uses **Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP)** natively. TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` for filtering. The tree node path is `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThis matches any assembly, any namespace, the `SmsNotificationTests` class, and all tests within it. The `--` separates `dotnet test` args from MTP args.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c29372ee-f863-4909-8388-c6fb8b62b108","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, you use `--treenode-filter` to filter tests. To filter by class name, the syntax would be:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit uses MTP natively, so `dotnet test` may or may not work depending on the version. Actually, with recent versions of dotnet test and MTP, `dotnet test` should forward to MTP.\n\n\nThe tree node filter path follows the pattern `/AssemblyName/Namespace/ClassName/TestName`, so filtering by the `SmsNotificationTests` class uses `--treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"`. Since TUnit is MTP-native and typically configured as an Exe project, I'd run it with `dotnet run` and the filter flag, though `dotnet test` should also work with MTP support. The full namespace is `Contoso.Notifications.Tests` and the class is `SmsNotificationTests`, so the tree node filter would be `/TestProject/Contoso.Notifications.Tests/SmsNotificationTests/*` to match all tests in that class. I'll provide the user with the `dotnet test` command using this filter.","outputTokens":758,"requestId":"A02A:2C9D9E:D6FC72:FCB386:69FE8F75"},"id":"bd56df93-82f2-4eeb-87f2-98896ec194a4","timestam